description.plain:
Will Smith is a famed actor who has so many iconic movie roles in Hollywood blockbusters under his belt you sometimes forget he’s an accomplished rapper, too.

Smith started as the MC of the hip-hop duo “DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince,” with his childhood friend Jeffrey “DJ Jazzy Jeff” Townes as turntablist and producer. They gained critical acclaim and won the first Grammy awarded in the Rap category (1988).

As a result of spending money carelessly, Smith was nearly bankrupt in 1990, when the NBC television network signed him to a contract and built a sitcom, The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air, around him.

The show was successful and began his acting career. Smith has since gone on to become one of the most well-known and highest paid actors in the world.

This would later be revealed to be his own kids after he gets married to Jasmine’s bridesmaid.

songs.full_title: Gettin' Jiggy wit It by Will Smith
songs.title: Gettin’ Jiggy wit It

description.plain:
The first hit single from Will’s 1997 album Big Willie Style, this song was so significant that the particular time period in hip-hop from which it came is often called “The Jiggy Era”.

It certainly represents those years in which rap music became ultra mainstream; marked by flashy videos, shiny suits, club-oriented beats, and forgettable lyricism.

The track samples “He’s the Greatest Dancer” by Sister Sledge and borrows from the intro of The Bar-Kays song “Sang and Dance”. Nile Rodgers once mentioned that “Gettin' Jiggy wit It” was one of his favorite tracks that sampled his band Chic.

“Gettin' Jiggy wit It” went to #1  in the US in March 1998, reaching the top spot in its third week on the chart and staying there for three weeks. It also reached the top 20 in several other countries. Billboard declared it the #14 song of 1998. The track also received five Grammy nominations, winning Best Rap Solo Performance.

Smith told Blender Magazine that the single was doing well, but after Jerry Seinfeld said the line, “I was ready to get jiggy with it” on an episode of his show Seinfeld, that’s when the song ‘just went through the roof’.

Later, “Gettin' Jiggy wit It” was featured on the 2004 soundtrack for the film Shark Tale, which starred Will Smith.

Although it was once thought that Nas had ghostwritten the song, the rapper revealed in a 2014 Reddit AMA that “Will Smith wrote that song.”

“Gettin' Jiggy wit It” is remembered both positively and negatively by the media. VH1 named it one of the Greatest Songs of the 90s and GQ said in 2015 that it “somehow aged perfectly”. However, Pitchfork called it one of the 7 worst songs of the 90s.

description.plain:
This is the theme song from the 1999 steampunk film Wild Wild West starring Will Smith. Though the song was commercially successful and reached No. 1 on the Billboard Hot 100, it received widespread criticism for its verbatim sampling of Stevie Wonder classic “I Wish”, one of many choice cuts from his critically acclaimed Songs in the Key of Life; it was also criticized for being nowhere close to a “Western” kind of song (not that that was a bad thing).

“Wild Wild West” would later end up on Will Smith’s second studio album Willenium. The music video ended up being a star-vehicle for Dru Hill member Sisqó.

Why was Kool Moe Dee brought on to this project? It may have something to do with this 1987 track….

The opening track of Will Smith’s 2002 album Born to Reign, and the lead single of both this album and the soundtrack to his movie Men in Black II in the same year. “Black Suits Comin' (Nod Ya Head)” is the second song Smith made about the Men in Black, this time making reference to events and characters in the second movie and generally saying that the MiB are back for another round.

This song differentiates itself from the previous movie’s theme by not using any samples and being played out in a rap-rock style. It also features a different singer in the hook: Tra-Knox.

songs.title: Freakin’ It

description.plain:
The third and final single, released March 22 2000, from Will Smith’s second solo album Willenium.

Produced by Trackmasters and sampling Diana Ross’s “Love Hangover”, the songwriters of which (Pamela Sawyer and Marilyn McLeod) helped co-write this track along with Nile Rodgers and Bernard Edwards of Chic, and of course Big Willie himself.

Though not as commercially successful as many of his other singles, it’s still regarded as a favorite amongst fans, and is a perfect example of Will Smith’s corny, family-friendly rap at it’s best.
